[1] Portuguesa
Date: Fri 21 Oct 2005
From: Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: El Universal, Caracas, Venezuela, 21 Oct 2005 [trans. by
Jorge Gonzalez] [edited]
<http://www.eluniversal.com/2005/10/21/pol_art_21109A.shtml>

The Mayor of Guanare municipality, Portuguesa State, Mr. Rafael
Calles, confirmed the death of 8 persons because of yellow fever in
this community. He explained that a massive vaccination campaign was
carried out within the state and that in Guanare more than 65 000
persons have been immunized, which represents almost 90 per cent of
the total population in the area.
He pointed out that the majority of victims were from most distant
rural areas, so symptoms were not detected in a timely fashion, and
he declared unofficially that there were 8 deaths. In this way the
presumption of a yellow fever outbreak and the alert implemented
several weeks ago in this region of the country were confirmed.
Until yesterday, Portuguesa sanitary authorities had not recognized
the existence of affected persons, and they were referring to a
single case; however, the Mayor of Guanare, who was in Barquisimeto
yesterday promoting the Los Llanos International Fair, confirmed the
above account but pointed out that these were unofficial figures.
An emergency plan has been implemented, he indicated, and vaccination
is carried out in all health centers, in pharmacies, and even in city
councils. There is a regional campaign in order to educate and alert
people with respect to the disease.
2 suspected cases of yellow fever might have been treated in Pastor
Oropeza Social Security hospital in Barquisimeto, even though the
head of the hospital, Dr. Mario Jimenez, denied this version.
The alert came up yesterday morning, when a sign was placed in the
entrance to the Emergency Room, indicating that access was forbidden
because of contamination. The sign read "emergency consults are
suspended until further notice. We inform the public that the room is
contaminated. No trespassing". A woman who was about to enter the
hospital because of a severe stroke was turned away and referred to
another health center.
However, soon after trying to get information from the head of the
hospital, and when [Jimenez?] denied the [reports of a] possible
yellow fever outbreak affecting his patients, the sign was taken out.
With regard to the affected persons and that are hospitalized, it was
known that they are a couple from Maracay, Aragua state, and that
they have a child that may also undergoing medical testing.
--
