******
[2] Country-wide
Date: 19 Oct 2005
From: Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Epidemiological Bulletin, Ministry of Health. Epidemiological
week no.40, 2-8 Oct 2005. [trans. Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://www.msds.gov.ve/msds/Boletines/Alertas/2005/Alerta40.zip>

For this 41st Epidemiological Week, 2 cases of yellow fever were
notified: one in Apure State, San Fernando municipality, Arichuna
village, and the other in Bolivar State, Raul Leoni municipality,
Campo Grande area. Epidemiological surveillance continues in
high-risk states. In the mentioned areas no other human cases have
been reported, but it is suspected that there are epizootics, since
there are rumours about deaths of araguato monkeys in the area (45
minutes drive from the site of the case).
Epizootic rumors were investigated by state health personnel.
Surveillance flights were carried out, and a private plane was rented
in order to perform vaccination and control activities in these
hard-to-reach areas.
Up to Epidemiological Week 41, 5 cases of yellow fever had been
reported, corresponding to the following Epidemiological Weeks: 17 (1
case), 20 (2 cases in Merida state), 35 (1 case in Apure state), and
36 (1 case in Bolivar state). In the curve, there are 2 peaks for
investigated cases that correspond to epizootics reported by this
coordination and to the large number of cases investigated when there
was a leptospirosis outbreak affecting Carabobo, Miranda, and Aragua states.
With regard to the registry for 2005, up to 41st Epidemiological
Week, 507 suspected cases had been investigated, and 5 cases of
yellow fever had been reported. In 428 cases yellow fever had been
ruled out. Amongst them, 282 cases do not have a definitive diagnosis
yet, 17 were dengue fever, 86 were hepatitis A, 0 were hepatitis B,
35 were leptospirosis, and there are 72 pending results.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is a discrepancy in the counting of YF cases between the 2
reports. It may be due to the reason that the official weekly update
appears to be 2 weeks behind the current date. - Mod.RY]
